ary to counterculture, these technologies challenge them as well, pointing, however unwittingly, to the violently classed, gendered, and racialized blind spots such fantasies harbor. More broadly, the technologies answer concerns that films control violence too much or too little. Offering neither mere discourse nor mere thrills, they recover sense and sensation for all, not some, or even most, depictions of bloodshed. As figures, the devices also remediate vision and violence for film theory, which exhibits distrust for each in spite of the complexities phenomenology and psychoanalysis have brought to cinematic perception and pleasure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aMotion pictureszUnited States. 0aViolence in motion pictures. 4aAmerican Studies : American Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Popular Culture. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Mass Media. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846541840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438465418423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438465418/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles